hallenge and openly resist the progressively intolerant policies of the Spanish Crown. Timely and resonant—given current debates concerning Islam, minorities, and cultural and linguistic assimilation—this edition provides scholars in a range of fields with a vivid and early example of resistance in the face of oppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMoriscosxCultural assimilationzSpainzGranada (Province). 0aMoriscoszSpainzGranada (Province)xHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  alatin america, regional, country, government, leadership, royalty, royals, memo, colonial, kingdom, city, occupation, conversion, converts, muslim, prejudice, religion, faith, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, christian, christianity, letter, 16th century, 1500s, renaissance, middle ages, protest, assimilation, laws, legal, castilian, translation.1 aBarletta, Vincent.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226547282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226547282/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles